The file system of the Linux : 
---------------------------------


                                                     "/"
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
|           |               |               |               |                   |

/bin        /etc            /home          /Sbin            /temp               /root
"user       config_file     user's_home    System_binary    /Temporary_file     all file show 
binary"


----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Linux command is the case_sensetive : 
--------------------------------------
>>> command option  argument 
>>> ls  -arl        /Desktop


----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
file related command: 
---------------------
>>> pwd => show the current directory . 

>>> mkdir => make directory. 

>>> touch => create file . 

>>> ls   => show the content of a folder / dir . 

>>> cat file_name => show the content inside of the file . 

>>> less => show the file content in buttom part . 

>>> head => default display the first 10 lines .  

>>> tail file_name => show the content of file . 

>>> tail -f => follow the end of a chaning of file 
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
#special command for 'tail' : 
------------------------------

- `tail -n 10 testCommand.txt` â†’ Show the last 10 lines (default is 10).
- `tail -f testCommand.txt` â†’ Continuously display new lines as they are added (useful for logs).
- `tail -c 50 testCommand.txt` â†’ Show the last 50 bytes of the file.


Let me know if you need anything else! ğŸš€
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

check the position of the folder: 
-----------------------------------
>>> cd . => current directory . 

>>> cd .. => parent directory move / back . 

>>> cd ~ => goto home for normal user. 

>>> cd # => goto home for the root . 

>>> cd / => goto the root dir. 

